Female alarm calls while it circled me on the ground, ruff up, from 2 metres away in Staghorn Sumacs. Time of 8:52 a.m. EDT.

A covey of about six chicks followed the hen across the logging road as we drove along. Two chicks were caught and began to give alarm calls. The rest of the chicks disappeared under cover while the hen called. The hen spread her tail and ruff and "meowed". She ran around nearby while hissing and made other distracting noises until both chicks were released. While calling, the female stalked along the underbrush, spreading her tail and ruff as she vocalized.

Weather: Wind. Other Behaviors: Emit Alarm.

location.name: Lesser Slave Lake PP--Martin River Campground

mediaNotes: Very interesting set of vocalizations. Recording Time: 1:03:00 PM (UTC -6). Temperature: 17 C. Habitat: Boreal/Taiga, Mixed Coniferous/Deciduous. Background species and behavior notes: Setophaga coronata, Vireo olivaceus.  Seen female Ruffed Grouse, presumably near nest or young. We startled each other as I was walking down the path. She was initially strutting toward me hissing (probably before the track started), then yowling, again moving toward me and hissing, doing a kind of broken wing display. She scurried away from me to one side of the path and then to the other, then flew up about 2-3 m into a tree and sat there scolding. Uploaded photo was taking with an Iphone. Background noise is wave noise from lake about 200 m distant. Specific Location: Latitude 55.47941653, Longitude -114.89805295, Elevation 605 m. Marten River Campground, Lesser Slave Lake Provincial Park, 23 km NNE bearing 339) of the town of Slave Lake. ID'd by Sight & Sound ; ID confidence 100%.
Flushed from the trail, the bird then sat in a small tree, ~1 meter off the ground and called for about two minutes. Once I started the voice recording, it flew off into the forest.
Frantic alarm calls given by adult when we suddenly crossed paths on the trail. A few high-pitched squeaks from the chicks can also be heard.
